    <prp:abstract>We propose ALMA Band 7 observations purposed to search for a circumstellar disk and a molecular outflow around the very young protostar Cha-MMS1.  The object possibly represents a transition stage from a first hydrostatic core to a Class 0 protostar. The rapidly rotating dense envelope has a large specific angular momentum which is likely to favour early disk formation. On the other hand, the rotation axis is aligned with the general magnetic field direction in the region. Models including non-ideal MHD effects but assuming ordered magnetic field structure, predict the formation of an initially small disk (R &lt; 10 AU), whereas according to the turbulent collapse models a large disk (R~ 50-100 AU) can form early.  We will determine or confine the disk size, mass, and orientation, and estimate the launching radius, speed, and opening angle of the putative outflow at a spatial resolution of 30 AU.  The detection of a resolved disk would strongly advocate the turbulence-induced disk formation model, an upper limit would mean that disks are born small. </prp:abstract>
